Project Draft

2023-04-17

Data

The data set Most-Recent-Cohorts-Institution.csv was collected to form Institution-level data files to form aggregate data for each institution. This data includes, location, enrollment, student aid, and costs. This data was collected to just help get an idea for the U.S department of Education to get a general idea about all of the universities in the United States.

Introduction:

All the students here have come from various backgrounds but still ended up at the University of Wisconsin-Madison. We have decided to find correlations between race, gender, and location to see how these factors affect the chances of admission at each university in the United States.The questions we have chosen to create an analysis on is Does the acceptance rate of a school depend on location (east coast/west coast)? How does race and gender differ in admission of east coast and west coast schools? Are SAT and ACT cutoffs of schools similar based on location? Or is it based on the school’s merit? The data collected from Institution-level data files on all universities, that provides us with the acceptance rate, ethnicity, gender, and ACT/SAT scores of colleges, lets us investigate the potential impact of location on acceptance rates, race and gender in admissions, and potential differences in SAT/ACT cutoffs.

Background:

This data was collected to form Institution-level data files to form aggregate data for each institution. This data includes, location which is either east coast or west coast, acceptance rate of the certain university, Ethnicity, gender for the university, and ACT and SAT average acceptance rate. This data was collected to just help get an idea for the U.S department of Education to get a general idea about all of the universities in the United States.

Source: http://api.data.gov/ed/collegescorecard/

We are splitting the country in half into East coast and West coast based on the longitude of the universities. This is the case based on how we will be comparing the universities on the west coast to the universities on the east coast. We will look at Ethnicity and gender specifically and compare to see how the East coast and the West coast schools compare. One unusual factor that could have a major impact on the data is Covid in 2020. This is the case because acceptance rates could be different and many of the other variables could be affected based on this outside factor. Where we are splitting the data to be east coast or west coast could also have an impact on the data and the interpretation of the results. This is the case because everyone could have a different interpretation of being on the East coast or West coast. We intend to answer the questions of Does the acceptance rate get affected based on location of schools? How does race and gender differ in admission of east coast and west coast schools? Are SAT and ACT cutoffs of schools similar based on location? Or is it based on the school’s merit?

Q4 95% confidence interval of Admission Rate Averge Based on Location:

>This graph is very basic and it shows where the percentiles lay for the averege admission rates based on East coast or West coast. This also gives us a good idea as of what the mean would be based on where the line is.

## # A tibble: 2 × 5
##   location       n  mean    sd      SE
##   <chr>      <int> <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 East Coast   684 0.679 0.212 0.00809
## 2 West Coast   378 0.715 0.197 0.0101
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  west$adm_rate
## t = 70.6, df = 377, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6952373 0.7350728
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  0.715155

We are 95% that the mean of the Administion rate based on the location of west coast schools is between 69.523% and 73.507%.

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  east$adm_rate
## t = 83.909, df = 683, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6627284 0.6944868
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
## 0.6786076

We are 95% that the mean of the Administion rate based on the location of east coast schools is between 66.2728% and 69.44868%.

##

##  0.1130225 0.1491446
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 0.6916160 0.5605325
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
##

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6260919 0.6523657
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x  mean of y 
## 0.69161601 0.05238719

First one we are 95% that the mean of the Administion rate based on the race of white people is between 11.30% and 15%. Second one we are 95% that the mean of the Administion rate based on the race of Asian people is between 63%% and 65%.

Discussion

Q1 The results from this summary suggest that there is not a significant difference between the average acceptance rate in the east coast compared to the west coast. In regards to our question of interest, which is whether the location has an effect on the acceptance rate, overall it seems that the location (east or west coast) does not have a big correlation with the acceptance rate. A shortcoming of this analysis may be that we used a bar graph, we may use another graph that better represents the data. New data that we are interested in collecting will be the acceptance rate per year. This would enable us to see the trend over the years in the difference between the west and the east coast in terms of the average acceptance rate. As shown from the bar graph, there is no significant difference between the average acceptance rate in the east and the west coast.

Q2 For the White race and Black race, the east coast has higher percentages compared to the west coast. For the Hispanic race and Asian race, it is the opposite, with the west coast having higher percentages than the east coast. In both the east and west coast, the White race is the most prevalent. Between all the races, the Asian race has the lowest percentages both in the east and west coast. It is also clear that the Hispanic race has a percentage in the west coast that is double the one in the east coast, while the other races has a smaller percentage difference between the west coast and the east coast.

Q3 In both the west and east coast, the female percentage is greater than the male percentage. However, the percentage of females in the east coast is slightly larger than the percentage of females in the west coast, while the male percentage in the west coast is larger than the east coast.

So we are trying to find based on if the college is located on the east coast or west coast and see how confident we can be with where the average admission rate will be. The first thing that I noticed that could be a issue with our data is the number of colleges that are on the East coast is far more then the number of colleges on the west coast causing our data to be more accurate on the east coast then west coast. We can see based on our table that we printed that the mean of both the east coast and the west coast are very similar and its just a difference of 3.5 percentage points. The standard deviation of both are also very similar and we can see that 21% of people are within one standard deviation of the mean on the east coast and 19.7% of people are within one standard deviation of the mean on the west coast. Based on the 95% confidence interval that we did we can determine that the average administration rate will be between 69.523% and 73.507% on the west coast, and between 66.2728% and 69.44868% on the east coast. So how can we interpret this data, we can interpret this data as we are more confident that you have a better shot at being accepted into schools on the west coast based on the ranges. However, the range is greater on the west coast and this is the case maybe based on the number of schools on the west coast and us having less data to pull from. However, we can be more accurate on the average range on the east coast schools even if you are a little less likely to be accepted to a east coast school.
